@syazwan0913 You could, in theory, do this with CSS. When you "Edit Dashboard" there's an option to add CSS. If the number and sequence of these Big Number components on your dashboard is static, you can use CSS nth-of-type trickery. I made a quick example to illustrate the case:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/812905/68715696-70252e80-0557-11ea-931d-3942573b9a88.png)

Syles applied here are as follows.

1) Set the background color of each instance.
```
.superset-legacy-chart-big-number:nth-of-type(1){
    background: orange;
}
```

2) Put the subheader where you want it (you can set the width so it wraps, etc.)
```
.superset-legacy-chart-big-number .subheader-line {
    text-align: left;
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 10px;
    left: 10px;
}
```

3) Add a CSS pseudo element, and give it the icon you want as a background.
```
.superset-legacy-chart-big-number:nth-of-type(1)::after {
    content: '';
    display: block;
    height: 60px;
    width: 60px;
    background: url(https://image.flaticon.com/icons/png/512/121/121901.png);
    background-size: contain;
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 20px;
    right: 20px;
}
```

That's super hacky, but might get you the result you want without having to make new components.

@graceguo-supercat This looks like a good improvement to me!  I'm wondering about a couple enhancements, which I can look at in a follow-up PR if you'd like:

• Would it be even better if just the individual tree were to scroll? In this case, that would be just the right side's tree. Optionally, it could even leave the Expand/Collapse/Search pinned to the top. 

• I see the Less file has some significant-looking static values (128px, 64px, ...). I didn't look super closely at these, but if they're making space for other elements (i.e. a header), would it add value to use Less variables, so that we can tweak more easily in the future? I've been meaning to make a pass at the Less files in general looking for this sort of thing, hoping we can use more Less variables for "style guide" kind of things.
